**Time Complexity:** O(m*n)
**Space Complexity:** O(m*n)

**Some tips I use to become better at Top-down DP (feel free to give suggestions):**
1. When thinking in top-down DP manner, always begin with termination conditions. (What happens when i reaches the end or when j reaches the end?)
2. What happens when we encounter a special condition? (e.g. What happens when p[j-1] == '*'?)
3. In a top-down manner, since the **final** result will only be available when we hit the termination condition, when we increment i or j, it means that we can 'omit' either one or both of them. For instance, when p[j] and s[i] matches or when p[j] equals to the "match everything" special character, we can increment both i and j (by 'omitting' them and only consider characters after i and after j)
4. Always think recursively. Memoization can be as simple as one line (which can be achieved by the cache decorator in Python)
5. Practice and practice. Good luck!

**Steps I follow when I do bottom-up DP (suggestions are welcome):**
1. Start with base condition (e.g. What if both strings are empty? i.e. dp[0][0] = True. What if one string is empty and another is not? Pre-populate those values)
2. When we say dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1], it means we can 'increment' i and j, similar to top-down manner. This is because we can omit calculation for current string and simply "bridge the cap" with the previous results. (Not sure if this makes sense)

