Here i am having a recursive solution in python. 

> Lets understand the complexity of the problem and where we are not able to pass the cases.

In this problem we need to  match two string char by char the problem while doing is the REGEX  <bold>* </bold> and<bold> ?</bold> which creates confusion. Genralization comes with equating the length of the char  as we encounter the <bold> * </bold> and <bol> ? </bold> following are the cases that we need to follow:

> 1. text = 'xyz'  and  pattern = '*' -> In this we can directly return true as '*' can match anylength of sequence without any issue.
> 2. text = 'xyz' and pattern = 'x?z' -> Here, also we can return true as '?' can match with length 1 char which will give true as result.
> 3. text = 'xyylmnz' and pattern = x <bold>* </bold>m?z -> Now a little confusing part here we need to match the text as much as possible so we will match 'yyl' with  '<bold>* </bold>' and then 'n' with '?'  and so we will get all char matched with text.

Apart from the above cases we might encounter a case where we don't have '*' and '?' in the string and that is simple case of string matching where we don't need to worry about REGEX patterns.

