This is a regular O(N^2) DP solution, but we do a trick by adding a character "#" to the head of both expressions s and p (or add any other character as long as it's not in the given char set). Then, we don't need to worry about edge cases where p[0] = '*' or '?', etc.

Runtime: 9 ms, faster than 95.15% of Java online submissions for Wildcard Matching.

```
public boolean isMatch(String s, String p) {
	s = "#" + s;
	p = "#" + p;
	int sn = s.length(), pn = p.length();
	boolean[][] dp = new boolean[pn][sn];

	dp[0][0] = true;
	for (int i = 1; i < pn; i++) {
		if (p.charAt(i) == '*') {
			for (int j = 0; j < sn; j++) {
				if (dp[i-1][j]) {
					for (int k = j; k < sn; k++) {
						dp[i][k] = true;
					}
					break;
				}
			}
		} else {
			for (int j = 1; j < sn; j++) {
				if (dp[i-1][j-1]) {
					dp[i][j] = (p.charAt(i) == '?' || p.charAt(i) == s.charAt(j));
				}
			}
		}
	}

	return dp[pn - 1][sn - 1];
}
```

