solutions.content:
## Explanation

One only needs to write the code to the corresponding block.

The concept is exactly how recursion works.
We:

- only traverse while the stack is not empty.  (#0)
- push a left child to the stack right after a pre-order region.  (#3)
- push a right child to the stack right after an in-order region.  (#6)
- pop the stack right after a post-order region.  (#8)

And there are some implementation details:

-  If a traversal is not a in-order nor post-order traversal, it's a pre-order traversal. (#1)
-  Use a `while (true)` with a `if` statement inside to ensure `node` is not null outside the loop.  (#2, #4)
-  If a node has no right child, the in-order operation and post-order operation happen simutaneously. (#5, #7)
-  `prev` is the last post-order traversed node. (#9)

## Template

```C++
        stack<TreeNode*> stack{};
        TreeNode* prev = nullptr;

        if (root)
            stack.push(root);
        while (not stack.empty()) {  // #0
            TreeNode* node = stack.top();

            if (not prev or
                prev != node->left and prev != node->right) {  // #1
                while (true) {
                    // Pre-order region {
                    //   do_something();
                    // }
                    if (not node->left)
                        break;   // #2
                    node = node->left;
                    stack.push(node);  // #3
                }
            }
            // #4
            if (not node->right or prev != node->right) {  // #5
                // In-order region {
                //   do_something();
                // }
                if (node->right)
                    stack.push(node->right);  // #6
            }

            if (not node->right or prev == node->right) {  // #7
                // Post-order region {
                //   do_something();
                // }
                stack.pop();  // #8
                prev = node;  // #9
            }
        }
```

