## ***Please Upvote my solution, if you find it helpful ;)***

# Intuition
We want to reverse a character array in place, meaning we cannot use any additional memory like creating a new array.
To achieve this, we will use the two-pointer approach, where we place two pointers, i and j, at the two ends of the array. We'll swap the characters at these pointers to reverse the array.
# Approach
1. We will use two pointers, i and j, initialized to the start and end of the array, respectively.
1. While i is less than j, we will perform the following steps:
- Swap the characters at positions i and j.
- Move i one step forward (towards the middle) by incrementing it.
- Move j one step backward (towards the middle) by decrementing it.
- We keep repeating the above steps until i is less than or equal to j. When i becomes equal to or greater than j, the whole array will be reversed.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
The two-pointer approach runs in linear time $$O(N)$$, where N is the length of the character array. This is because each element is swapped at most once.

- Space complexity:
The space complexity is constant $$O(1)$$ because we are not using any additional memory that grows with the input size. We are modifying the given array in place.
# Code
```java []
class Solution {
    public void reverseString(char[] s) {
        // Iterate from the beginning (i) and end (j) of the array towards the middle.
        for (int i = 0, j = s.length - 1; i < s.length / 2; i++, j--) {
            // Use a temporary variable (temp) to store the character at index i.
            char temp = s[i];

            // Replace the character at index i with the character at index j.
            s[i] = s[j];

            // Replace the character at index j with the character in the temporary variable (temp).
            s[j] = temp;
        } 
        // At this point, the character array 's' contains the reversed string.
    }
}
```
