Funny problem and one that really teaches you to squeeze all the info/hints you can get in the description.

Ruling out a lame and very expensive sorting approach - no fun at all, I decided to start with a linear solution that just checked each single element in the `1 - n` range.

To do so, we create first of all a few support variables:
* `len` will store the length of the input vector;
* `seen` is an array of `len + 1` booleans;
* `res` is a vector of 2 elements (since LC really seems to love vectors instead of pairs or tuples) where we will store our result.

We will then first of all set all the the cells from `1` to `len` (included) in `seen` to `false`.

Successively, we will parse `nums` to either mark the cell matching value in `seen` if it is was not explored or assigning it as the first value in `res` if encountered before. Yes, I did it a bit hack-ish, just to have more fun.

The last step will have us check for the sole value in the `1 - len` range which was not marked in `seen` as the number that was not in the series and thus to be stored as the second one in `res`.

Once encounteres, we can return `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findErrorNums(vector<int>& nums) {
        // support variables
        int len = nums.size();
        bool seen[len + 1];
        vector<int> res(2);
        // preparing seen
        for (int i = 1; i <= len; i++) seen[i] = false;
        // parsing nums and finding the first part of res
        for (int i: nums) seen[i] = (!seen[i] || bool(1 + (res[0] = i)));
        // parsing seen and finding the second part of res
        for (int i = 1; i <= len; i++) if (!seen[i]) return res[1] = i, res;
        return res;
    }
};
```

The brag:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2d5c8c13-e7e1-411d-ac41-968a509be4c6_1614731862.2765493.png)


Variant solution in which we use the second loop also to increase a new accumulator variable `tot` that will end up having the sum of all the elements in `nums`.

Once we have that, we can just remember that the Gaussian formula for sum of all the numbers in the `1 - len` range, which is `len * (len + 1) / 2`: that would have been the correct sum if not replacement of a number was ever done, so we can conclude that `len * (len + 1) / 2 == tot + res[0] - res[1]` (with `res[0]` as the repeated number which has been added and `res[1]` as the number which originally should have been there).

Reversing the formula we have that `res[1] == len * (len + 1) / 2 - tot + res[0]`.

The more efficient code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findErrorNums(vector<int>& nums) {
        // support variables
        int len = nums.size(), tot = 0;
        bool seen[len + 1];
        vector<int> res(2);
        // preparing seen
        for (int i = 1; i <= len; i++) seen[i] = false;
        // parsing nums and finding the first part of res and to compute tot
        for (int i: nums) {
            tot += i;
            seen[i] = (!seen[i] || bool(1 + (res[0] = i)));
        }
        // computing the second part of res
        res[1] = len * (len + 1) / 2 - tot + res[0];
        return res;
    }
};
```

But do we really need extra memory? Well, probably no, if we notice that all the numbers which we will be given are positive, so we can use an old trick and flag the visited ones setting them to be negative.

To do so, we first of all declare a few variables: `len`, `tot` and `res`, same as above.

We will then parse each element `n` of `nums` and:
* be sure that `n` is positive, coverting it to its absolute value;
* increase `tot` by `n`, same as in the previous solution;
* deal with the edge case of `n == len`, setting `n` to `0` to handle overflow and cover also the first element;
* check if `nums[n]` is negative (ie: pointing to an already visited node):
	* if so, we set `res[0]` to `n` (or to `len`, if its original value was still `0`);
	* if not, we mark it as visited turning it to its negative value.

Once done, we can derive `res[1]` with the same magic used above and we are done :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findErrorNums(vector<int>& nums) {
        // support variables
        int len = nums.size(), tot = 0;
        vector<int> res(2);
        // parsing nums
        for (int n: nums) {
            // normalising n
            n = abs(n);
            // increasing tot
            tot += n;
            // preventing overflow
            if (n == len) n = 0;
            // finding the duplicate or marking numbers as visited
            if (nums[n] < 0) res[0] = n ? n : len;
            else nums[n] *= -1;
        }
        // computing the missing element
        res[1] = (len + 1) * len / 2 - tot + res[0];
        return res;
    }
};
```

