**APPROACH**

For solving any problem, clarify what is it that we need?
If we read this problem, we can understand that we need two numbers, one that is repeated and the other that should take its place. 
We can find the repeated number by using a HashSet. A hashset stores all elements in it only once. We can iterate over our given array and keep adding the elements to a set, we will also put a check to see if the number that we currently want to add is already in the set or not. If the number is already in the set, we have found the repeated number and we can break out of the loop, since there is only one repeated number. 

Now to find the number which should have been there in the array, we can use simple mathematics. We see that the numbers in the array are in the range of 1 to n where n=length of array and from the question we know : " You have a set of integers s, which originally contains all the numbers from 1 to n. " 

So the actually sum of the array should have been 
**Actual_Sum= n(n+1)/2**, from Arithmetic Progression Series

but the sum is not so due to the repeated element,

So since we have found our duplicate element, the real element should be
**Real_Element= Actual_Sum-Sum_CurrentArray+DuplicateElement**

Hence, 
Find the sum of elements of the given array and subtract this sum from the actual sum calculated from the formula and add the duplicate number to it. 

```
class Solution {
    public int[] findErrorNums(int[] nums) {
        int n=nums.length;
        // to store the answer to be returned
        int[] ans=new int[2];

        HashSet<Integer> set=new HashSet<>();

        //storing the sum of the elements in the given array
        long sum_current=0;
        for(int x:nums)
            sum_current+=x;

        //finding the duplicate element
        for(int i=0;i<nums.length;i++)
        {
            if(set.contains(nums[i]))
            {
                ans[0]=nums[i]; //stores the duplicate element
                break;
            }
            set.add(nums[i]);
        }

        // sum of elements from 1 to n
        long sum_actual=(n*(n+1))/2;
        int realElement= (int)(sum_actual-sum_current+ans[0]);
        ans[1]=realElement;

        return ans;
    }
}
```

**TIME COMPLEXITY:** O(N)
**SPACE COMPLEXITY:** O(N)

