solutions.content:
Consider the word 'apple'. For each suffix of the word, we could insert that suffix, followed by '{', followed by the word, all into the trie.

For example, we will insert following into trie:
```
'{apple', 
'e{apple', 
'le{apple', 
'ple{apple', 
'pple{apple', 
'apple{apple'
```
 Then for a query like prefix = "ap", suffix = "le", we can find it by querying our trie for 
 ```
 'le{ap'
 ```

The idea behind the use of '{' is because it's ASCII value is comes just after 'z'. So, use of '{' as separator will help in reducing checks for separator.
```
letter  ASCII code
-------------------
a          97
z          122
{          123
```

```
class WordFilter {
	/*standard trie node to store each character. observe carefully, #child is 27 to accomodate the separator '{' */
    struct node{
        int weight;
        struct node* child[27];
    };
    struct node* trie;

	/*create new node using malloc and allocate it's weight to be 0 & it's all chils as NULL */
    struct node* allocate(){
        struct node* ptr = (struct node*)malloc(sizeof(struct node));
        ptr->weight = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<27;i++){
            ptr->child[i] = NULL;
        }
        return ptr;
    }

	/*standard insert operation, everytime you insert word in trie, keep on updating the weights*/
    void insert(string &word, struct node* root,int weight){
        for(int i=0;i<word.length();i++){
            int idx = word[i]-'a';
            if(root->child[idx]==NULL)
                root->child[idx] = allocate();
            root->weight = weight;
            root = root->child[idx];
        }
        root->weight = weight;
    }
