Three tips to help others avoid making the same mistakes I made:
1. When they say maximum weight - "return the word with given prefix and suffix with maximum weight" - return the **highest valued indexed word** that has matching prefix and suffix (see ```max(res)``` in the code)
2. **Use memoization** to keep track of the results of queries that were already made, this will make the difference between TLE and accepted on some tests.  
3. Don't forget to reverse the suffix before searching for it in the suffix-tree.  

The gist of the code is as follows: Create two Trie.  One a prefix tree (words are read forwards) and the other a suffix tree (words are read from back to front).  At each node in the tree, store **the indices** of all the words that are connected to that node in ```self.words```.  For each query, trace the prefix down the prefix-tree to find the set of words indices that have that prefix.  Do the same for the suffix on the suffix-tree and return the largest index that appears in both results.  

Hope this helps!

```python
class Node(object):
    def __init__(self, val):
        self.val = val
        self.children = {}
        self.words = set()

class Trie(object):

    def __init__(self):
        self.root = Node(None)

    def insert(self, index, word):
        curr = self.root
        curr.words.add(index)
        for char in word:
            curr.words.add(index)
            if char not in curr.children:
                curr.children[char] = Node(char)
            curr = curr.children[char]
        curr.words.add(index)

    def find(self, string):
        curr = self.root
        for char in string:
            if char in curr.children:
                curr = curr.children[char]
            else:
                return set()
        return curr.words

class WordFilter:

    def __init__(self, words: List[str]):
        self.prefix = Trie()
        self.suffix = Trie()
        self.memo = {}

        for i,word in enumerate(words):
            self.prefix.insert(i, word)
            self.suffix.insert(i, word[::-1])


    def f(self, prefix: str, suffix: str) -> int:
        k = (prefix, suffix)
        if k in self.memo:
            return self.memo[k]

        a = self.prefix.find(prefix)
        b = self.suffix.find(suffix[::-1])
        res = a&b

        self.memo[k] = max(res) if res else -1
        return self.memo[k]
